Here are some interesting facts on Vietnam from the famed Gallup Poll Monthly-May 1990:<br>
1,225 adults aged 18 and older (in May 1990) were polled by the Gallup poll in what was supposed to be a statistically valid sample.  They said some interesting things-their answers and the results were:<br><br>
1. Which one of the following presidents do you think was most responsible for getting our country into Vietnam? <br>
Dwight Eisenhower-13%<br>
John F. Kennedy-23%<br>
Lydon Johnson-36%<br>
Richard Nixon-17%<br>
Other-1%<br>
No Opinion-10%<br><br>
2.  Which president was most responsible for getting us out?<br>
Johnson-10%<br>
Nixon-48%<br>
Ford-31%<br>
Other-2%<br>
No Opinion-9%<br><br>
3.  Thinking of Americans soldiers who lost their lives in the Vietnam War, do you think they died in vain or not?<br>
Died in vain-51%<br>
Did not die in vain-41%<br>
No opinion-7%<br>
Refused to answer-1%<br><br>
4.  In your opinion, have Vietnam vets been treated well by people of the US in the years since the Vietnam War, or not?<br>
Yes-26%<br>
No-69%<br>
no opinion-5%<br><br>
5.  Have the Vietnam vets been treated well by the United States government in the years since the Vietnam War, or not?<br>
yes-24%<br>
no-67%<br>
no opinion-9%<br><br>
6.  Have you visited the Vietnam War memorial in Washington DC?<br>
yes-16%<br>
no-84%<br>
25% of those 18-24 years old have visited as well as 26% of college graduates and 23% of men 35 to 45 years old.<br><br>
IGNORANCE ABOUT THE WAR<br>
67% polled know the US fought on the side of South Vietnam-19% think the US sided with North Vietnam and 14% didn't know.<br>
Only 12% know that betweem 50,000 to 60,000 soldiers were killed in Nam.  One American in ten believes more than half a million Americans were killed in Nam.  45% believe more Americans were killed in Vietnam than during other US wars this century.<br>
In the 18 to 24 year old category, 30% think the US sided with the North and 63% think more Americans died in Vietnam than during World War II.<br><br>
Anti-war demonstrations<br>
Of those polled 5% admitted to being a part of demonstrations against the war.  3% particiapted in demonstrations in support of the war.  91% didn't participate in any demonstrations.<br>
  (How's that for apathy????)<br>
Also, looking back only 25% wished they had made a stronger protest against the war.  67% said they wouldn't have made a stronger protest against the war and 8% had no opinion.<br><br>
Vietnam Service and Veterans<br>
74% believe it was a mistake to be in Vietnam.  Only 25% of those polled felt Vietnam was a just war.<br><br>
87% of those polled hold a favorable view of nam vets, 5% hold a unfavorable view of Nam vets and 8% had no opinion.<br><br>
Of those polled 57% either served or had a relative or close friend serve in Vietnam.  42% didn't serve in Vietnam, nor did they have a relative or friend who served and 1% had no opinion on the matter.<br><br>
